e rise of modern Europe. Taken together, Liebert’s analysis of this context, including the nuance of Gibbon’s relationship to Christianity, and his readings of Gibbon’s better- and lesser-known texts suggest a historian more eager to comprehend Christianity’s worldly power than to sneer at or dismiss it.Eminently readable and wholly accessible to anyone interested in or familiar with the Decline and Fall, this groundbreaking reassessment of Gibbon’s most famous work will appeal especially to scholars of eighteenth-century studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aChristianity. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600xHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Georgian Era (1714-1837).2bisacsh  aAutobiography.  aChristianity.  aEarly Modern Travel Writing.  aEdward Gibbon.  aEighteenth-Century History.  aFall of Rome.  aHistoriography.  aHistory of Religion.  aRise of Christianity.  aRoman Empire.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271092430423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271092430/original  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK